# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acc-trophy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acc-trophy/1996-acc-trophy] The **1996 ACC Trophy** was a cricket tournament in Malaysia, which took place from 6 to 16 September 1996.
[src:acc-trophy/1996-acc-trophy] It gave Associate and Affiliate members of the Asian Cricket Council experience of international one-day cricket and also helped form an essential part of regional rankings.
[src:acc-trophy/1996-acc-trophy] The tournament was won by Bangladesh who defeated the UAE in the final by 108 runs.
[src:acc-trophy/1996-acc-trophy] The teams were separated into two groups of six.
[src:acc-trophy/1996-acc-trophy] The top two from each group qualified for the semi-finals.
[src:acc-trophy/1998-acc-trophy] The **1998 ACC Trophy** was a cricket tournament in Nepal, taking place from 3 October to 13 October 1998.
[src:acc-trophy/1998-acc-trophy] The tournament was won by Bangladesh who defeated Malaysia in the final by 8 wickets.
[src:acc-trophy/1998-acc-trophy] This would be Bangladesh's final ACC Trophy title prior to their elevation to Test status in 2000.
[src:acc-trophy/1998-acc-trophy] The teams were separated into two groups of five.
[src:acc-trophy/2000-acc-trophy] The **2000 ACC Trophy** was a cricket tournament held from 15 to 24 November 2000 in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:acc-trophy/2000-acc-trophy] The tournament was won by the host nation, who defeated Hong Kong in the final by three wickets.
[src:acc-trophy/2000-acc-trophy] This was the United Arab Emirates' first title.
[src:acc-trophy/2000-acc-trophy] The eight teams were divided into two groups of four, with the top two from each group qualifying for the semi-finals.
[src:acc-trophy/2002-acc-trophy] The **2002 ACC Trophy** was a cricket tournament held from 10 to 21 July 2002 in Singapore.
[src:acc-trophy/2002-acc-trophy] The tournament was won by the United Arab Emirates, who defeated Nepal in the final by six wickets.
[src:acc-trophy/2002-acc-trophy] This was the UAE's second consecutive title.
[src:acc-trophy/2002-acc-trophy] The ten teams were divided into two groups of five, with the top two from each group qualifying for the semi-finals.
[src:acc-trophy/2004-acc-trophy] The **2004 ACC Trophy** was a cricket tournament in Malaysia, taking place between 12 and 24 June 2004.
[src:acc-trophy/2004-acc-trophy] It gave Associate and Affiliate members of the Asian Cricket Council experience of international one-day cricket and also helps forms an essential part of regional rankings.
[src:acc-trophy/2004-acc-trophy] The tournament was won by the UAE who defeated Oman in the final by 94 runs.
[src:acc-trophy/2004-acc-trophy] The teams were separated into four groups: three groups of four teams and one group of three teams.
[src:acc-trophy/2004-acc-trophy] The top two from each group qualified for the quarter-finals.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] The **2006 ACC Trophy** was a cricket tournament in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, taking place between 14 August and 26 August 2006.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] It gave associate and affiliate members of the Asian Cricket Council experience in international one-day cricket.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] This was the last tournament in which all teams played in the same tournament.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] After this tournament, the Asian Cricket Council decided to split the tournament into two divisions.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] The top ten teams would be promoted to the 2008 ACC Trophy Elite and the rest of the teams would be relegated to the 2009 ACC Trophy Challenge.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] There were 17 teams that played in the tournament.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] These teams were non-test member nations of the Asian Cricket Council.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] Top two from each group qualifies for the quarterfinals.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] The teams that win their matches qualify for the semifinals.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] The losing teams compete for 5th place in the plate semifinals.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] The teams that win their matches qualify for the final.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] The losing teams compete in the third place playoff.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] The top eight were ranked on their performance in the quarterfinals and playoffs.
[src:acc-trophy/2006-acc-trophy] The rest were ranked based on the points and net run rate attained during the group stage.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] A series of six **ICC World Cricket League** (WCL) tournaments, as well as a series of pre-qualifying regional tournaments, and the 2009 Cricket World Cup Qualifier were played between January 2007 and April 2009.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] It was the first use of the World Cricket League structure.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] Through the WCL tournaments, teams could advance to the World Cup Qualifier, which could lead to qualification for the 2011 Cricket World Cup.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] 30 Associate and Affiliate members of the ICC participated in the events.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] The Afghanistan national cricket team ascended from Division Five to Division One by winning three of these tournaments and performing well in the World Cup Qualifier.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] The league structure was organised with the five global divisions.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] The regional tournaments were administered by the five Development Regions of the International Cricket Council: Africa, Americas, Asia, East Asia-Pacific, and Europe.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] The following is the summary of World Cricket League and its structure.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] This was followed by the International Cricket Council.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] The above diagram shows the chronological order and structure of the divisions within the World Cricket League.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] From left to right the chronology of the divisions is indicated; from top to bottom the hierarchy within the competition.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] Japan were relegated to 2009 Global Division Seven.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] All other teams 7th or lower were distributed into lower divisions.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] 1st to 6th received official One Day International status for the following four years.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] 1st to 8th qualified for the ICC Intercontinental Cup.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] The United States had their membership suspended and were replaced by Argentina in Division Three in 2007.
[src:acc-trophy/2007-2009-icc-world-cricket-league] Upon reinstatement, they were assigned to Division Five in 2008.
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] The **ACC Trophy** was a limited-overs cricket tournament organised by the Asian Cricket Council (ACC).
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] Open only to associate and affiliate members of the International Cricket Council (ICC), it was contested biennially between 1996 and 2012, but was replaced by the three-division ACC Premier League in 2014 as the primary limited-overs competition for non-Test-playing ACC members.
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] The tournament was discontinued for 9 years, and reinvented as ACC Premier Cup in 2023.
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] The finalists of the 2000 and 2006 tournaments qualified for the Asia Cup, where matches had One Day International (ODI) status.
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] The inaugural edition of the tournament was played in Malaysia in 1996, and featured 12 teams in a single division.
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] The single-division format continued until the 2006 tournament, which featured a record 17 teams.
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] The ACC Trophy was then split into "Elite" (first-grade) and "Challenge" (second-grade) divisions, with the first editions held under this format being the 2008 ACC Trophy Elite and the 2009 ACC Trophy Challenge (the latter tournament was the only one to be held in an odd year).
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] The two-division format continued until the final tournament in 2012, with promotion and relegation between divisions.
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] Only six teams – Hong Kong, Malaysia, the Maldives, Nepal, Singapore, and the United Arab Emirates – competed in all nine editions of the ACC Trophy, although the Maldives and Singapore were relegated to the "Challenge" tournament at various stages after the introduction of two divisions.
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] The UAE was by far the most successful ACC Trophy team, with five wins (and four consecutive victories from 2000 to 2006).
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] Bangladesh won the first two tournaments, but were rendered ineligible after gaining Test status.
[src:acc-trophy/acc-trophy] Notes: Bangladesh gained full Test status in 2000 and are no longer eligible to participate in the ACC Trophy.
